			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">This is a great read from one of the EQII board moderators.  He drove to SD (home city of SoE) to check out their plant site and get the scoop on EQ2.  This is the kind of thing that gets your blood flowing about EQ2 as it did in the original days of EQ.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
Alright, what you're about to receive is probably not what you were expecting. I didn't go down to SOE, beat on the door, then sit there for three hours repeating "where's the class list! Where's the class list, huh, huh? C'mon, I know you have it. And what about beta? Spill it. C'mon guys. What classes are there? Where's my beta disc bitches? Why are you taking so long? Tell me. Tell me now. Yeah, class list and beta. That's right, you heard me! I know you know I'm here. You can't ignore me forever now! Hey, what's this all about? Now you're calling security on me? Screw you guys! GIMME CLASS INFOZ." 
<br />

<br />
That's probably what you would've liked me to do, but that ain't my style. And to be honest, that was never my intention in the first place. I've been watching this game for a long while now, and considering how much I've written about it, the fact is, my experience with it was the fifteen minutes I saw at E3 like everybody else and nothing more. Well I wasn't content with that; I wanted to really form an impression of the game. Really take a look at it and judge my own reaction to it. 
<br />

<br />
Seriously, if I went in there and harassed them about a Class Tree and Beta Info for my entire visit, all I would've got was a prepared line, and probably the door smacking my ass on the way out. Same thing goes for general questions. I could've lobbed question after question at them, and chances are I would've got pretty much the same information we already have. 
<br />

<br />
Truth is, as a writer, there are certain realities I've accepted about the MMOG industry. First off, it's a business, second off, it's a BIG BUSINESS. I know you all know this already, but what it means is that these guys are professionals. 
<br />

<br />
Fact is, these guys know when they're going to release the Class Tree. They know how much of a big deal it is, and they have what they feel is a right time to release the information. Same goes with beta. It's not like I can just walk into SOE and say, "hey guys, you know, I'd really like to see a Class List" and they'd be all "oh really? We didn't know that. Wait, I think I've got one lying around here somewhere. Maybe it's in the trash. Oh no! Wait! Here it is. I'm using it as a coaster for my coffee. Now I need a new coaster... I guess I'll just use this BETA disc I have lying around." 
<br />

<br />
See, that's not how it works. I'm not saying you can't be pissed that they don't pleasure you with info lovin on a more regular basis, that's up to you, but in my own opinion it would've been a waste of a visit if all I did was ask questions that can't be answered, or questions that I could just as easily ask over email (and have not answered). Instead, what I got a chance to do was sit down, get a chance to hang out with some of the EQ2 guys (at one point in time there was myself and seven other SOE guys hanging out in John Blakely's office) and really form an impression on this game we've all followed for so long. 
<br />

<br />
This is how the story goes... 
<br />

<br />
Thanks to Sean Kauppinen of Sony Online Entertainment (Gaming Public Relations), he managed to schedule me in for 1:30 Wednesday afternoon. I knew where the Sony buildings were located, though I hadn't actually seen them yet. Arriving ten minutes before I was scheduled, I got my first look at where everything takes place. 
<br />

<br />
Man, what can I say, three buildings, several stories high, entirely covered in black tinted glass. You can't see in whatsoever. For all a passerby might know, it's some secret military complex. The place just oozes "badass" and we're not talking, compensating for something that's not there. Let's face it, metaphorically speaking SOE is the porno sized wang of the MMOG industry. No camera tricks here, just pure, frightening dominance. And what can I say, it's a mite bit intimidating. All the doors to the three buildings are electronically locked, so the only way to get in is talk into a little black box to a security guard. 
<br />

<br />
Though I think the guard took one look at me, and as I'm pretty much the antithesis of threatening, he let me in with little hassle. Once in, as you can imagine, the dialogue went something like this: 
<br />

<br />
Guard: "WhoTF R U?" 
<br />
Me: "Imma Anyuzer" 
<br />
Guard: "NOS UR NOT. UR LIK 13" 
<br />
Me: "STFU CORPORATE DOG!" 
<br />

<br />
...alright I lie, it actually went nothing like that. It went more a long the line of him, glaring at me in silence with a look that said without a single syllable, "what the hell are you doing here?" 
<br />

<br />
The inside of the first building I was in (what little of it I saw) was certainly nice. Comfortable couch to sit on, some nice EQ art work up on the walls, a few gaming magazines. Feeling assured that if the security guard made any moves to get rid of me, I was going to flee through the dark interior of the building screaming "HLEP!" until I got arrested. Thankfully enough, before I had to resort to such desperate tactics, Sean strolled in. 
<br />

<br />
Not surprisingly enough, I don't think he was expecting me (few people are at first), but upon being introduced, he shook my hand and we were off. Now when I'm in this sort of situation, I'm fairly quiet. It's not that I don't have things to say, but I never bring a pad of paper or pen with me. Instead I just make mental notes as I take everything in. So I just nodded dumbly, as he led me from the first building into a second building where the Everquest 2 project is in development, pointing out various points of interest as we went. 
<br />

<br />
Finally, we got to John Blakely's office, I got to meet John Blakely (Senior Producer) finally for more than the three minutes I saw him at E3, and before I knew it, the room was filling up with other EQ2 names that I was excited to meet. Like a flood, the decent sized office of Blakely's was filled up to overflowing with Bill Trost (Lead Designer), Moorgard, Sean Kauppinen and Andrew Sites (Producer). There were also a few other people, like Stuart Compton who stopped by for awhile. 
<br />

<br />
Now I can tell you right now, you can't imagine how cool this was. Try to imagine being in a room with many of the minds behind the EQ2 project. These people knew the game in and out, what was even better they were excited to show me it! I mean, I was expecting like a ten minute, "here's the game, good, good, we're busy, see you later." It couldn't have been further from the truth. These guys treated me like gold! 
<br />

<br />
Well maybe not like gold, because if they had a gold bar they'd probably spend most of their time rubbing it and moaning, and they did not spend the entire time rubbing me and moaning. I swear! And no, that's not what I had to do to get into the SOE buildings (pssst, the security guards are suckers for a courtesy reach around... just kidding). 
<br />

<br />
Really though, they treated me exceptionally well. They were comfortable around me, Blakely booted up the live build of Everquest 2 and the demo, accompanied by the best play by play (all the EQ2 guys with me in the room) I could possibly ask for. 
<br />

<br />
Now, the live build is an interesting thing. It's something that really impressed me, so I think you guys will be impressed as well. From what was explained to me, there is an in house EQ2 server for the EQ2 employees to play on. Every day there is a 'live build' updated onto it. This live build is constantly changing, things are being gutted, experimented with, refined, smoothed out, and so on. What dictates these changes, apart from the set milestones the development team runs by, is the fact that it is required that all employees working on the EQ2 project play at least twice a week. They then make a list of everything they didn't find fun, and those problems are discussed. I know you're all saying, "what the hell do I care? It's not like I'm playing EQ2" at which point I say, "woah, this is pretty important stuff!" The thing is, the effect this will have is very far reaching into the core of the game. Is it fun? If it's not, it'll be changed. This shows an open mindedness and a willingness to actually change things for the better. I believe this will go a long way in delivering an exceptionally refined and finished product. 
<br />

<br />
What mechanics were in, and weren't in the live build Blakely showed me, I couldn't really tell as I'm not familiar enough with them to notice what was, or wasn't there. What I could see easily right away though were a few things based on the visuals alone. First was the fact that while I sat there, and time flowed past, visually the game simply awed me. If you think you've glimpsed the beauty of this game in screenshots, or in a badly compressed E3 video, I can assure you right now, you don't have a clue. I didn't say much as I stared at this game for the entire session, not because I didn't have anything to say but because I think if I opened my mouth I would've started giggling like an excited school girl. Tehehehehehehe. See, I can hardly help myself now and its days later. 
<br />

<br />
The second thing that was very noticeable visually was the smoothness. Do you remember people worried after E3, due to the jerkiness they saw on screen? There were naysayers all over the place, exclaiming basically that the game was too advanced, and there was no way in hell it would run on anybodies computer. As was pointed out to me, in Blakely's office, it was simply an ignorant accusation and attack. Fact is, at E3 very little graphical optimization had been done. 
<br />

<br />
Now we're somewhere in the 50% range I believe and I didn't notice the game jerk once. It ran as smooth as silk, and not on some super military computer either. Blakely's computer isn't that far off from mine, which, while closer to a top of the line machine (2.6ghz I believe, with a GFFX 5900), is nothing out of this world. Once optimization is fully done, I expect it will run quite nicely on computers less than this, so for all of you worried that you'll have to buy a brand new computer, this may alleviate some of your concerns. 
<br />

<br />
Blakely ran quickly through character customization (and he did it at least a dozen more times as he was creating various characters for various reasons) and the process is just stunning. It excites me just thinking about it. Let's face it, we all like character creation. There is something decidedly fresh, and enjoyable about starting a brand new character from scratch and being able to mold him to your own will. Well, we already knew this, but it was certainly reinforced for me, EQ2 simply has the best character customization I've seen in any game so far. The amount of possible combinations are just mind boggling. It was reinstated that there is a goal for people to be recognizable by their character customization choices alone. An impressive goal without a doubt. 
<br />

<br />
I'd like to quickly say, at this point, as things were progressing, I was exceptionally impressed with these guys attitude. They were joking around, very comfortable with each other, laughing a lot and showing that they had a real interest in EQ2 turning into the best MMOG available. Having Bill Trost exclaim loudly "It's always the gnomes fault! Those bastards!" will certainly go down in infamy as one of my favorite EQ2 quotes. Hell, they'd even read my promise to spray paint <a href="http://www.eqii.com" target="_blank">www.eqii.com</a> across myself and attempt to get myself arrested if I didn't get in to see them (and they threatened to bring the spray paint!). Really though, the air was filled with a certain attitude, the feeling that these guys weren't uptight and stressed out, only able to spit out "we haven't done that yet! That hasn't been implemented yet! We can't do that! We don't know when we'll get that in!" instead they seemed quite relaxed and very happy with the progress of the game. I read into this type of thing, and to me this was certainly an important factor. They were happy, they were having fun and they were confident. All the traits you want to see in a development team that really believes in what they're doing. 
<br />

<br />
At this point I was given a tour of some player housing. It is instanced of course, so that every player will be able to own housing of some sort if they wish it, unlike the Guild Housing. I'll admit right now, player housing was the feature I was least excited about in EQ2. Hell, I just don't really care about owning my own house... well at least I didn't. Just for fun they took me on a tour through the size of the house and the customization options for it. Well hot damn! For the first time in any game, I'm suddenly interested in having my own place. Once again, it seems they applied much the same philosophy to player housing, that they did to character customization, which is: give the people the options. Let the players decorate the cosmetic side of things how they will. I believe a line has to be drawn somewhere (I'm a firm believer against armor dyes for example), but beyond a shadow of a doubt, the more options for housing the better as far as I'm concerned. And I'm talking everything. Paint, molding, ceiling, floor, it looked like you could pretty much change whatever part of player housing that you wanted. Not to mention that, with the ability to place stuff pretty much wherever you want, the nature of Player Housing and how it will positively effect storage is very obvious. 
<br />

<br />
After this, the amount of stuff these guys talked about, joked about, pointed out to me and flew me through was just overwhelming. It was all about the little things, like getting a feel for the true size of Freeport (which was massive). Or being shown an interesting conning system they&#8217;re working on. Or just watching how the NPCs actually look at you. Depending on where they are, and what their attention is focused on, their heads follow you as you pass, and they might even call something out to you. It's nearly creepy it's so realistic. 
<br />

<br />
Then to hear the developers talk about the game itself. They point out how NPCs will talk about players, and will be far more dynamic. They're excited when they tell me how different merchants will want different things, and how merchants further away from the main cities of trade will price things more expensively to make up for that distance. When John Blakely attacks a creature, and a chest drops, they eagerly show me how rogues will be able to unlock chests as a main ability, while any class can smash the chest open, items have a probability of getting damaged or even destroyed in the process. Cleverly, it tells you what items you damage or destroy when you do smash the chest, so you can groan if it was something you wanted, and how rogues will even gain experience for successfully picking a lock. 
<br />

<br />
How players will be gaining experience through more than just killing. Through exploring, and quests, and even other things possibly, just in the natural flow and progression of the game. I mean, the little things go on, and on, and on. There will be quests that procure more than a simple item, but actually routes of quicker travel, and possibly other things. Hot damn! The list goes on and on. 
<br />

<br />
You know though, all of those things really were inconsequential to me. What I got to see, and what was shown to me, was by far more important in my opinion. I got excited again. It's not that I ever lost my excitement, but I'm a bit of a cynic, and while sitting there, hearing the developers point out various things as John Blakely ran around, I found myself eager to play the game. Giddy nearly at the thought of this. Now I'm not much of a fanbois, in fact I make a pretty sucky one, I'm usually far too skeptical to ever find myself that impressed with something where I literally WANT IT NOW. 
<br />

<br />
That was exactly the impression that was formed for me. The feel of the game was amazing; it was epic in scope, and deep in complexity. The world for a second took me back into that fantasy world. There was ambiance to it and life, and it was even empty of any players, but I could still feel it. For a brief moment, the magic I felt when I first entered Everquest was back! And I wasn't even playing. 
<br />

<br />
I suppose you guys were hoping for more information, a Class Tree, etc. Thing is, what I really wanted to bring back was an assurance for all of you whose enthusiasm has been wavering, that this project we're interested in is indeed looking to be a quality project. The team working on it is, dedicated and energetic. In other words ITS WORTH BEING EXCITED ABOUT. If you look at the screenshots and exclaim "Holy Crap! I want to play that!" then you're along the right lines. Everything you've seen so far is actually surpassed by the real thing. 
<br />

<br />
Finally, Blakely spent at least a good hour just flying me around. This world is massive. For those of you who really felt like Star Wars Galaxies lacks in static content, Everquest 2 has it in spades. The world is insane in size, and all entirely hand crafted and unique. I'm talking dungeons and caves and towers. Rolling fields and farmhouses. Creepy lighthouses, meteor scarred landscapes, swamps, statues, ruins, cities. Everything is there. Truly a playground for adventurers. From what I saw in Everquest 2 and I am now confident to say that I saw the near future of gaming. This is the game that will raise the bars for MMOGs. Demand higher standards and more features. If you can't compete at this level, you simply can't compete. Get ready people, because I believe Everquest 2 may just change the way we game. 
<br />

<br />
PS. I did ask one question though, because I figured if I got one piece of clear information, it was better than a lot of half assed information. I asked whether it was 48 Final Classes or 48 Total Classes. At the moment it was explained to me to be 48 Total Classes, though I was assured that is primarily a working number. It is not set in stone. So for all of you class tree nuts out there, hopefully that may provide a bit of clarity as you attempt to build your own class trees.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
